Lesson 7 – Operating Systems & Processes (CS) vs File Management & Collaboration (IT)

Do Now What you'll learn Key Vocabulary Activities Plenary

Do Now

Quick review of Lessons 1–6 (CS vs IT; Algorithms vs Workflows; Binary; Programming vs Productivity; Networks; Databases vs Spreadsheets).

Match each statement to the correct topic:

1. Breaking a task into precise steps a program can follow.
Answer: Algorithm / Programming (CS) — L2 / L4.
2. Sharing a document with the class and giving view‑only access.
Answer: Online services & Permissions (IT) — L5.
3. Turning numbers into characters or pixels.
Answer: Binary / Data Representation (CS) — L3.
4. Choosing between a spreadsheet and a database for a club list.
Answer: Spreadsheets vs Databases (IT/CS) — L6.

What you'll learn today

By the end of this lesson, you will be able to:

  • Say what an operating system does (processes, memory, files).
  • Organise files with clear names, folders, and permissions.
  • Pick examples that belong to CS OS internals vs IT file collaboration.

How you'll know you've got it

  • Describe two OS jobs (e.g., manage memory, run programs).
  • Set up a tidy folder structure with sensible names.
  • Explain when to use view vs edit access.

Key Vocabulary

Operating System (OS) — the main software that manages the computer.
Process — a running program.
RAM — fast memory used by active programs.
Storage — where files are saved (SSD/HDD/cloud).
File system — how files/folders are organised.
Permission — who can view, comment or edit.
Sync — keeping files up to date across devices.
Version history — past changes you can roll back to.

Main Activities

CS Track – OS in Action

  1. List 3 jobs the OS does when you open a program.
  2. Explain what happens if RAM is full (swap/virtual memory).
  3. Extension: why do background processes matter?
# Example ideas
# - Loads the program into RAM
# - Schedules CPU time for processes
# - Manages files the program opens

IT Track – Tidy & Share

  1. Create a folder tree for a school project (Docs/Slides/Data).
  2. Use names like 2025-10-28_Project_Title_v01.
  3. Share with a partner: set view or edit and explain why.

Compare & Reflect

  • How does the OS support file management?
  • When do permissions help protect work?
  • Where have you seen OS and collaboration tools work together?

  • 🟨 Hands up if you liked both.
